8 PROPOSED OVERSIGHT COMMITTEE SUBSTITUTE
9 An Act relating to entertainer safety; creating the
Entertainer Safety and Verification Act; defining
10 terms; prohibiting performances by exotic
entertainers without proper identification;
11 prohibiting owners of sexually oriented businesses
from allowing performances by exotic entertainers
12 without certain verification; directing business
owners to secure copies of certain documents;
13 requiring business owners to maintain records for
certain period of time; making certain records
14 confidential and exempt from open records
requirements; providing for the inspection of records
15 by law enforcement; making certain acts unlawful;
providing penalties; providing for codification; and
16 providing an effective date.
17
18
19 BE IT ENACTED BY THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF OKLAHOMA:
20 SECTION 1. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
21 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 1029.1 of Title 21, unless there
22 is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
23 This act shall be known and may be cited as the "Entertainer
24 Safety and Verification Act".
Req. No. 16636 Page 1

1 SECTION 2. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
2 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 1029.2 of Title 21, unless there
3 is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
4 As used in the Entertainer Safety and Verification Act:
5 1. "Commercial sex" has the same meaning as such term is
6 defined in Section 748 of Title 21 of the Oklahoma Statutes;
7 2. "Exotic entertainer" means any person who performs live
8 entertainment in a sexually oriented business including, but not
9 limited to, dancing, stripping, or similar performances, where the
10 entertainer appears in a state of nudity, semi-nudity, or engages in
11 sexually suggestive or lascivious conduct;
12 3. "Human trafficking" has the same meaning as such term is
13 defined in Section 748 of Title 21 of the Oklahoma Statutes;
14 4. "Lascivious" means the exposure of the genitals, pubic area,
15 anus, or female breast below a horizontal line across the top of the
16 areola, or any simulation thereof, with the intent to arouse or
17 gratify the sexual desire of any person;
18 5. "Lewdness" has the same meaning as such term is defined in
19 Section 1030 of Title 21 of the Oklahoma Statutes;
20 6. "Nude" means the showing of the human male or female
21 genitals, pubic area, or the human female breast below a point
22 immediately above the top of the areola, with less than a fully
23 opaque covering;
24
Req. No. 16636 Page 2

1 7. "Pandering" has the same meaning as such acts are described
2 in Section 1029 of Title 21 of the Oklahoma Statutes;
3 8. "Prostitution" has the same meaning as such term is defined
4 in Section 1030 of Title 21 of the Oklahoma Statutes;
5 9. "Semi-nude" means a state of dress in which clothing covers
6 no more than the genitals, pubic area, and areola of the female
7 breast, as well as portions of the body covered by supporting straps
8 or devices;
9 10. "Sexually oriented business" means an adult cabaret or any
10 other business, as such term is defined in Section 1040.55 of Title
11 21 of the Oklahoma Statutes, that offers live entertainment
12 characterized by the exposure of persons in a state of nudity, semi-
13 nudity, or engaging in sexually suggestive or lascivious conduct;
14 and
15 11. "Sexually suggestive" means any act or performance
16 involving the fondling or erotic touching of the clothed or
17 unclothed genitals, pubic area, anus, or female breast of oneself or
18 another, or any simulation thereof.
19 SECTION 3. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
20 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 1029.3 of Title 21, unless there
21 is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
22 A. No person shall be authorized to perform as an exotic
23 entertainer in a sexually oriented business in this state unless the
24 person:
Req. No. 16636 Page 3

1 1. Is a citizen of the United States or an alien lawfully
2 admitted to the United States and authorized to engage in employment
3 pursuant to the Immigration Reform and Control Act of 1986, Section
4 1101 et seq. of Title 8 of the United States Code, as verified
5 through the federal E-Verify program or a successor program approved
6 by the United States Department of Homeland Security;
7 2. Is at least twenty-one (21) years of age; and
8 3. Possesses a valid state-issued driver license or a current
9 government-issued identification document containing the photograph
10 of the person.
11 B. No owner, operator, proprietor, or manager of a sexually
12 oriented business shall knowingly permit any person to perform as an
13 exotic entertainer on the premises until verifying the citizenship,
14 age, and identification of the person.
15 1. All records for exotic entertainers including, but not
16 limited to, employment applications, personal contact information,
17 employment schedules, and any other identifying data submitted to
18 and maintained by the owner, operator, proprietor, or manager of a
19 sexually oriented business shall be confidential and shall not be
20 open to public inspection or disclosure pursuant to the provisions
21 of the Oklahoma Open Records Act.
22 2. Such records shall be maintained by the owner, operator,
23 proprietor, or manager for a minimum of twelve (12) months following
24 the last performance on the premises of the exotic entertainer. All
Req. No. 16636 Page 4

1 exot ic entertainer information and records shall be made available
2 immediately for inspection upon request by code enforcement
3 officials or law enforcement officers with jurisdiction for
4 investigatory purposes.
5 C. Failure by the owner, operator, proprietor, or manager of
6 the sexually oriented business to comply with the verification or
7 record maintenance requirements of this section shall constitute a
8 separate violation for each day of noncompliance.
9 SECTION 4. NEW LAW A new section of law to be codified
10 in the Oklahoma Statutes as Section 1029.4 of Title 21, unless there
11 is created a duplication in numbering, reads as follows:
12 A. Any sexually oriented business found to have violated the
13 provisions of Section 3 of this act shall be subject to an
14 administrative fine of Five Thousand Dollars ($5,000.00) per
15 offense. A second or subsequent violation shall be subject to an
16 administrative fine of Ten Thousand Dollars ($10,000.00) per offense
17 and suspension of all business licenses issued by the Alcoholic
18 Beverage Laws Enforcement (ABLE) Commission for a period of twelve
19 (12) months.
20 B. 1. Any owner, proprietor, manager, or operator of a
21 sexually oriented business who knowingly violates the provisions of
22 Section 3 of this act shall, upon conviction, be guilty of a felony
23 punishable by a fine not exceeding One Thousand Dollars ($1,000.00),
24 or by imprisonment in the custody of the Department of Corrections
Req. No. 16636 Page 5

1 for a period of not less than one (1) year nor more than three (3)
2 years, or by both such fine and imprisonment.
3 2. A second or subsequent violation of the provisions of
4 Section 3 of this act shall, upon conviction, be a felony punishable
5 by a fine not exceeding Five Thousand Dollars ($5,000.00), or by
6 imprisonment in the custody of the Department of Corrections for a
7 period of not less than two (2) years nor more than five (5) years,
8 and the person shall be permanently barred from owning or operating
9 a sexually oriented business in this state.
10 SECTION 5. This act shall become effective November 1, 2026.
